Change-Id: Ia62563b1677b78929b690357a6fa21fd7e85f331","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sakib-rahman-bangladesh/tensorflow/commits/2d0c38e8d7958b311e881537cc912b0c5c14d5cd"},{"sha":"8ffd110da5da70096f4fef635fa8ce7611432346","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Feed input tensors only if shape inference requires constant input

Currently, all constants are fed in the InferenceContext regardless of those are required for shape inference or not. This is wasteful and not even feasible for cases involving very large splat constants. It is not possible to create tensors requiring more memory than what is available on the host.

This may require multiple invocation of shape inference functions but this shouldn't add significant overhead as these functions are generally trivial.

Once the quantization information is stripped, the tensor can be uses as usual and raw_data op can be safely removed. The redundant cast ops with quantized type is not removed by cast op's canonicalization, but they are removed when they have no users after all tfr.quant_raw_data and tfr.quant_qparams ops are canonicalized.

Also moved canonicalization tests into a separate file, while adding a new test for quant_raw_data op.

* Replace flushDiscreteUpdates with flushSync

flushDiscreteUpdates is almost the same as flushSync. It forces passive
effects to fire, because of an outdated heuristic, which isn't ideal but
not that important.

Besides that, the only remaining difference between flushDiscreteUpdates
and flushSync is that flushDiscreteUpdates does not warn if you call it
from inside an effect/lifecycle. This is because it might get triggered
by a nested event dispatch, like `el.focus()`.

So I added a new method, flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering, which
is used for the public flushSync API. It includes the warning. And I
removed the warning from flushSync, so the event system can call that
one. In production, flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering gets inlined
to flushSync, so the behavior is identical.

Another way of thinking about this PR is that I renamed flushSync to
flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering and flushDiscreteUpdates to
flushSync (and fixed the passive effects thing). The point is to prevent
these from subtly diverging in the future.

* Invert so the one with the warning is the default one

To make Seb happy","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sj-rai/react/commits/32eefcb3c5131f4d77a2195ff11a00a2513cf62f"},{"sha":"ed6c091fe961a3b95e956ebcefe8f152177b1fb7","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Replace unbatchedUpdates with flushSync (#21776)

There's a weird quirk leftover from the old Stack (pre-Fiber)
implementation where the initial mount of a leagcy (ReactDOM.render)
root is flushed synchronously even inside `batchedUpdates`.

The original workaround for this was an internal method called
`unbatchedUpdates`. We've since added another API that works almost the
same way, `flushSync`.

The only difference is that `unbatchedUpdates` would not cause other
pending updates to flush too, only the newly mounted root. `flushSync`
flushes all pending sync work across all roots. This was to preserve
the exact behavior of the Stack implementation.

But since it's close enough, let's just use `flushSync`. It's unlikely
anyone's app accidentally relies on this subtle difference, and the
legacy API is deprecated in 18, anyway.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sj-rai/react/commits/ed6c091fe961a3b95e956ebcefe8f152177b1fb7"},{"sha":"9c7f29ebe75a7546e59038123d3b0c3515bec916","author":{"name":"Moti Zilberman","email":"8b603b22c9c89c36ffb170e88372622acf1aa8d8@gmail.com"},"message":"[WIP] DevTools: Support named hooks for >1 module in a bundle (#21790)

Change-Id: If8edc9e9bc915eab5a0285a6502a7bf56c6ed10a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Ending2015a/tensorflow/commits/27c5fa686e0f519e066b6da5118871ab4cb805f7"},{"sha":"103a3aa856caf1b539e9045ed6af4f3cec9015c0","author":{"name":"metarutaiga","email":"79dcb454b3ba32236f0276331d624b4cb6f2e888@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Rename IN / OUT to INPUT / OUTPUT for Windows on ARM","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Ending2015a/tensorflow/commits/103a3aa856caf1b539e9045ed6af4f3cec9015c0"},{"sha":"7959ae05ec674311ebea4e7ad919c9520bc0f40c","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Short-circuit CAS loop.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.

* Better documentation where if_delegate_has_method is inapplicable

We could also replace if_delegate_has_method in all cases, since the code might be more readable as @available_if(lambda self, method: hasattr(self.base_estimator, method))

Possible alternative naming of available_if: hasattr_if.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.

[{"sha":"8ffd110da5da70096f4fef635fa8ce7611432346","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Feed input tensors only if shape inference requires constant input

Currently, all constants are fed in the InferenceContext regardless of those are required for shape inference or not. This is wasteful and not even feasible for cases involving very large splat constants. It is not possible to create tensors requiring more memory than what is available on the host.

This may require multiple invocation of shape inference functions but this shouldn't add significant overhead as these functions are generally trivial.

The redundant cast ops with quantized type is not removed by cast op's canonicalization, but they are removed when they have no users after all tfr.quant_raw_data and tfr.quant_qparams ops are canonicalized.

Also moved canonicalization tests into a separate file, while adding a new test for quant_raw_data op.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[PJRT] Allow GPU memory oversubscription when unified memory is enabled.

With this CL, we can enable GPU memory oversubscription via env flags.
For example, `TF_FORCE_UNIFIED_MEMORY=1 XLA_PYTHON_CLIENT_MEM_FRACTION=8.0` provides 8x the GPU memory to the program. The 'extra' memory is physically located on the other GPU devices and the host's RAM, with swapping done transparently by CUDA.

When doing a compare-and-swap, if we ever get to the point where `old == new`,
just declare victory and exit.

Previously we'd continue doing the CAS with old == new until it "succeeded".

This particularly helps for scatters that

 - go from a large input to a small output (so there are many "collisions" on a
   given point), and

 - have many "nop" updates, for example with a max op, it's likely that most of
   the time you won't need to do anything because the value in the output is
   already larger.
